  "prompt": "Why does a concussion cause someone to throw up?",
  "response": "A concussion can cause someone to throw up due to the impact it has on the brain. When a person experiences a concussion, the brain can undergo a rapid back-and-forth movement within the skull, leading to temporary dysfunction. This movement can affect the part of the brain responsible for balance and coordination, known as the vestibular system, as well as the brain's ability to control automatic bodily functions, including nausea and vomiting.\n\nIn addition, the brain's chemical response to injury may also play a role in causing nausea and vomiting. After a concussion, the brain may release certain chemicals, such as neurotransmitters, that can trigger the vomiting center in the brainstem.\n\nOverall, vomiting after a concussion is the body's natural response to the disruption of the brain's normal functioning. It is important to seek medical attention if you or someone you know experiences a concussion and subsequent vomiting, as it may be a sign of a more severe injury.",
